message.content: Lupinus texensis, also known as the Texas bluebonnet, is a species of flowering plant in the legume family. It is native to Texas and parts of northeastern Mexico. The plant is characterized by its vibrant blue color and distinct petal shape, with a distinctive white spot in the center. Its leaves are green, narrow, and elongated, measuring up to 6 inches in length. The flowers of Lupinus texensis grow in upright spikes, reaching up to 12 inches in height. They bloom in the spring and summer months, typically from March to May. Lupinus texensis is often used as a symbol of Texas and can be found in fields, meadows, and along roadsides throughout the state.
